    {
      "id": "rcKLUFYEYCSQFzgiKltUe",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 379.3705162620689,
      "y": 2886.7623324192987,
      "width": 1196.2139699269264,
      "height": 307.71933705601964,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0i",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1188028896,
      "version": 841,
      "versionNonce": 628255750,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772103490775,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Issues\n1. The last write(), when there is no subsequent read(), such as in case of\ndispatching alerts\n-> I found out that in this case there is shutdown(socket_fd, SHUT_WR) \n \n2. The read() sequence without write(), such as when client sends TLS\nApplication Data -> s_server just reads without sending anything back\nIm thinking of pattern: read 5 bytes (pkt length) -> read packet",
      "fontSize": 30.771933705601963,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Issues\n1. The last write(), when there is no subsequent read(), such as in case of dispatching alerts\n-> I found out that in this case there is shutdown(socket_fd, SHUT_WR) \n \n2. The read() sequence without write(), such as when client sends TLS Application Data -> s_server just reads without sending anything back\nIm thinking of pattern: read 5 bytes (pkt length) -> read packet",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
